<span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Kick-off<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">At this point the group can learn about the background, for example the  Shitty Robots. It also seems helpful to give a short talk on the topic  \"Culture of Failure\" and how failure can move us forward.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":867572,"guid":"C4BBE920321611EA97DD61A657285094","previous_id":867571,"previous_guid":"B7905420321611EA97DD61A657285094","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"51F184D6A468427F9C97580188F69DCF","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"BADBBB8287014D93AF889C958FACC1F6","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Preparation<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Next, the group can be familiarized with the available materials. If  there are rules for group work, they can also be applied in this step as  well. Obviously, it is important to ensure that the rules encourage  rather than hinder creativity, experimentation and exploration.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":867573,"guid":"CF49EFE0321611EA97DD61A657285094","previous_id":867572,"previous_guid":"C4BBE920321611EA97DD61A657285094","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"C79E0FA3A99B4D7B90BB600BE37902A5","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"2F03AAE4698A49FD9EAEE4C7D7EBB8ED","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Shitty Model<\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">\n<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Now the participants may build or program their Shitty Model. This step  can and should take up a large part of the available time.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":867574,"guid":"DD193EF0321611EA97DD61A657285094","previous_id":867573,"previous_guid":"CF49EFE0321611EA97DD61A657285094","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"0F8F6379D99B435C8113C6EFE1441C38","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"78250B63096D4A47B63E29EFEDB9F853","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Presentation<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">After the models have been developed, the groups or individual  participants should present what they have achieved. This can be either  an entertaining show or a conventional presentation. The portfolio might  be presented, i.e. the different variants that may have been created.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":867575,"guid":"E9759D10321611EA97DD61A657285094","previous_id":867574,"previous_guid":"DD193EF0321611EA97DD61A657285094","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"91C6703B11864178A669A86E7F4F791F","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"F26E2EF84E92461D8FEA28718270315F","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Feedback<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Finally, the learning objectives should be reflected upon so that the  participants become aware of their own learning process. There is no  kind of correction or direct assessment of Shitty Models: There is no  right or wrong characteristic for these models. This last step is also a  good place to start the exchange: What were best practices? What were  the lessons learned?<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":null,"materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>This is the description of how the Shitty Models approach can be integrated e.g. into a lecture. The corresponding article can be found at Github (<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/github.com\/SommerEngineering\/blog-shitty-models\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">https:\/\/github.com\/SommerEngineering\/blog-shitty-models<\/span><\/a><span>) and on the website tsommer.education.<\/span><\/div><\/div>","changed_on":1578490444}